replyContent:
Hi Steffen, on the Start Screen press the cog symbol button (bottom right corner) to enter the Options menu and turn off SFX and Music.
We are sorry for the missing progress transfer to the full version. We tried Play Games cloud service and the Google cloud but both didn't work for our savegame system. We're still trying to find a solution. Thx.

A good challenge and a very fun game,  but business model is a bit annoying:  The free game only lets you play a few levels & then 2 dollars buys you the opportunity to advance through the other levels of the game.  An additional 3 dollars allows you to advance through the game, but with more building materials unlocked(essentially making the game  a less challenging sandbox game). In addition, if you get stuck and need help(a big possibility), you will be asked to pay for the hint.
replyContent: The game offers a 2,99$ in-app purchase to "unlock" all the levels in the game from the material and budget restraints, so that it changes from being a challenging puzzle game to more of a sandbox building game. We are sorry that it was misleading you to think we would demand to pay again to be able to play at all, which was not the case.

It's a great puzzle game. It could be so much better with a few improvements though:  (1) When a bridge fails, it's not always easy to tell which section failed first, and whether it failed in compression or tension. Some type of postmortem report would be nice.  (2) The concrete material seems to have infinite bending stress. That is, you can pull it to one side with a lot of tension and it never bends over and collapse to that side. This feels very unrealistic.  (3) The steel cables seem to have infinite tensile strength, at least I haven't yet seen one fail. This too feels very unrealistic.   (4) In addition to pass/fail, there is a score based on how much you came under budget. But I have no idea what constitutes a good score for each level. It would be nice if there was a "rating" for the score (e.g. 1 through 3 stars as done on Angry Birds).  (5) Each material obviously has a set of properties (tensile strength, compression strength, maximum length, cost per length) but I can't figure out how to display these properties.

This reminded me of a bridge building contest in I had in physics class, but instead of being restricted to wood, I can now simulate steel beams/cable, and cement anchors. The components of the bridge will change from green to red as the stress on that part changes due to the shift in the load. The materials each have their pros and cons: wood is economical and average in all regards, steel beams are expensive, heavy, but remarkably strong, steel cable is inexpensive and useless when compressed but excellent at tension, and finally cement being the best choice at compression but awful at torsion. None of the levels are extremely difficult, especially if you just breeze through using the cars as the load. But I don't see the free build mode that the change log hints at, just the ability to skip a level, which then allows free build for that particular stage. I think for this game to really make 5 stars, there needs to be a real sandbox mode and for there to be more types of load (rush hour, trains, etc) and maybe some more environments. As the app currently stands, it's definitely worth the $1.00 for what it currently offers.
